te\n| birth_name    = James Adelbert McDermott\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1936|12|28}}\n| birth_place   = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse        = Virginia Beattie McDermott <small>(\u20131989)</small><br>Therese Hansen <small>(1997\u20132012)</small>\n| children      = Two\n| residence     = [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n| alma_mater    = [[Wheaton College (Illinois)|Wheaton College]] ([[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]])<br>[[University of Illinois College of Medicine]] ([[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]])\n| profession    = [[Psychiatry|Psychiatrist]]<br>Assistant Clinical [[Professor]]\n| religion      = [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America|Episcopalian]]\n| allegiance    = {{nowrap|{{flag|United States of America|1912}}}}\n| branch        = {{flag|United States Navy}}\n| serviceyears  = 1968\u20131970\n| rank          = [[File:US-O4 insignia.svg|25px]] [[Lieutenant commander]]\n|unit           = [[Medical Corps (United States Navy)|Medical Corps]]\n| battles       = [[Vietnam War]]\n}}\n\n'''James Adelbert \"Jim\" McDermott''' (born December 28, 1936) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|WA|7}}, serving since 1989.  He is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].  The 7th District includes most of [[Seattle]], [[Vashon Island]], [[Tukwila, Washington|Tukwila]], [[Burien, Washington|Burien]], [[Shoreline, Washington|Shoreline]], [[Lake Forest Park, Washington|Lake Forest Park]], [[Lynnwood, Washington|Lynnwood]], [[Mountlake Terrace, Washington|Mountlake Terrace]], [[Woodway, Washington|Woodway]] and [[Edmonds, Washington|Edmonds]].\nHe serves on the [[U.S. House Committee on Ways and Means|House Ways and Means Committee]] and is a member of the House [[Progressive Caucus]].  He was formerly the committee chairman, then in 1995, ranking minority member on the [[House Ethics Committee]].\n\n==Early life, education, and early career==\nMcDermott was born in Chicago, Illinois. He was the first member of his family to attend college;{{citation needed|date=June 2013}} he graduated from [[Wheaton College, Illinois]], and then went to medical school, getting an [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] from the [[University of Illinois Medical School|University of Illinois College of Medicine in Chicago]] in 1963.{{citation needed|date=June 2013}} After completing an internship from 1963 to 1964 at Buffalo General Hospital in [[Buffalo, New York]], a two-year psychiatry residency at the University of Illinois Research and Educational Hospital (now called [[University of Illinois Research Hospital]]), and fellowship training in child psychiatry{{citation needed|date=June 2013}} from 1966 to 1968 at the [[University of Washington Medical Center]] in Seattle, he served in the [[United States Navy]] Medical Corps as a psychiatrist in California during the [[Vietnam War]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.seattlepi.com/local/280912_peacevets11.html?source=mypi | work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer | first1=Mike | last1=Barber | title=Sheehan offers refuge to war deserters | date=October 8, 2006}}</ref><ref>[http://www.house.gov/mcdermott/biography.sthml Retrieved 2007-03-25.]</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nIn 1970, McDermott made his first run for public office and was elected to the [[Washington State Legislature|Washington state legislature]] as a [[Washington State House of Representatives|representative]] from the [[Washington's 43rd legislative district|43rd District]]. He did not seek re-election in 1972 but instead ran unsuccessfully for [[Governor of Washington]]. In 1974, he ran for the [[Washington State Senate|state senate]], and subsequently was re-elected three times, to successive four-year terms.{{citation needed|date=June 2013}} During this time, he crafted and sponsored legislation that would eventually be called the Washington State Basic Health Plan, the first such state program in the country, which offers health insurance to the unemployed and the working poor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://medicare.commission.gov/medicare/mcdermott_bio.html |title=Medicare Commission |publisher=Medicare.commission.gov |date=December 28, 1936 |accessdate=April 11, 2013}}</ref> In 1980, while still a state senator, McDermott defeated incumbent [[Dixy Lee Ray]] in the Democratic [[primary election|primary]] for governor, but lost the [[Washington gubernatorial election, 1980|general election]] to Republican [[John Spellman]].  He ran again in 1984, losing the primary to [[Booth Gardner]], who then went on to defeat [[John Spellman|Spellman]] in the [[Washington gubernatorial election, 1984|election]].\n\nIn 1987, McDermott briefly left politics to become a [[United States Foreign Service|Foreign Service]] medical officer based in [[Zaire]] now known as [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], providing psychiatric services to Foreign Service, [[United States Agency for International Development|USAID]], and [[Peace Corps]] personnel in [[sub-Saharan Africa]].\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\nIn 1988, the seat for {{ushr|WA|7}} came open when five-term incumbent [[Mike Lowry]] gave it up to make an unsuccessful run for the Senate.  McDermott returned from Africa to run for the seat.  He won handily with 71 percent of the vote. McDermott has been re-elected 11 times with no substantive opposition.  He usually gets wide support in his district, the most Democratic white-majority district in the nation, even in disastrous years for Democrats nationally. In 1994, for instance, he won with 75% of the vote even as the Republicans won control of Congress and took all but two seats in Washington (his and that of [[Norm Dicks]]). He was re-elected in [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2010|2010]], taking 83 percent of the vote against independent challenger Bob Jeffers-Schroder. No Republican filed to contest the election in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |title=November 02, 2010 General Election |url=http://vote.wa.gov/results/20101102/CongressionalDistrict7.html |publisher=[[Secretary of State of Washington]] |date=November 29, 2010 |accessdate=February 8, 2014}}</ref> In 2012 McDermott was challenged in the Democratic primary by attorney [[Andrew Hughes (American politician)|Andrew Hughes]]. Despite spending more than $200,000 on his campaign (versus McDermott's primary spending of $387,000), Hughes won just 6-percent of the vote to McDermott's 71-percent.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://slog.thestranger.com/slog/archives/2012/08/21/hughes-spends-over-6x-more-per-vote-than-mcdermott | work=The Stranger | first1=Mike | last1=Gore| title=Hughes Spends Over 6x More per Vote Than McDermott | date=August 21, 2012}}</ref>In the general election, McDermott won just under 80% of the vote, against [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Ron Bemis.<ref>{{cite web|last=Reed|first=Sam|title=WA 7th congressional election results|url=http://vote.wa.gov/results/current/CongressionalDistrict7.html|work=2012 Election results|publisher=WA STATE SEC OF STATE}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n;AIDS Housing Opportunity Act of 1990\nIn his first term, the Congressman sponsored the AIDS Housing Opportunity Act, which provides state and local governments with the resources and incentives to devise long-term comprehensive strategies for meeting the housing needs of persons with AIDS and the families of such persons.<ref>[http://www.water1st.org/about/contact/advisory_council/jim_mcdermott.html ]{{dead link|date=April 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe program established, known as HOPWA, has grown to be a $335M line in United States budget, at a cost of $5,432 per recipient in 2010.  Despite the long-term focus of the original legislation, according to HUD, 59% of recipients received help with short-term housing.<ref>{{cite web|title=HUD HOPWA Overview 2010|url=http://blog.hud.gov/2011/04/14/updating-hopwa-funding-formula/|work=HUD Reviews HOPWA|publisher=U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development|accessdate=June 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\n;Cedar River Watershed Land Exchange Act of 1992\nThis consolidated land in Washington state which allowed the city of Seattle to gain greater control over its primary water source, thus enabling more efficient planning for the future.  The bill was one of the last signed by President [[George H. W. Bush]] before he left office.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19930825&slug=1717684 | work=The Seattle Times | first=Dick | last=Lilly | title=Seattle Journal \u2013 Watershed's End Run Worked | date=August 25, 1993}}</ref>\n\n;2002 Iraq Trip\nIn the fall of 2002, McDermott and fellow Representatives [[David Bonior]] of [[Michigan]], [[Nick Rahall]] of [[West Virginia]] and [[Mike Thompson (California politician)|Mike Thompson]] of California visited [[Iraq]]; in Baghdad they met with members of parliament and the Iraqi Foreign Minister, and in Basra they met with residents who talked about the effect on them of the [[Iraq sanctions]]. American conservatives sharply criticised McDermott for this trip, and for his predictions that President [[George W. Bush]] would \"mislead the American public\" to justify military action and that no [[Weapon of mass destruction|WMD]] would be found in Iraq.<ref>{{cite news |title=The story behind McDermott's controversial Iraq trip|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/politics/2004311506_mcdermott28m.html|work=Seattle Times|accessdate= 2011-06-02|first=David|last=Postman|date=March 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAfter this trip, McDermott's opponents dubbed him \"[[Baghdad]] Jim\";<ref>{{cite web |title='Baghdad Jim' questions timing of capture |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/3728223 |publisher=MSNBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Buzzing Over Baghdad Jim |url=http://realclearpolitics.blogs.time.com/2008/03/28/buzzing_over_baghdad_jim/#|publisher=Real Clear Politics | accessdate=May 6, 2010}}</ref> his supporters point out that he has been proven correct on the facts.<ref>Robert L. Jamieson, Jr., [http://www.seattlepi.com/jamieson/131032_robert16.html 'Baghdad Jim' was dead on about war], ''Seattle Post-Intelligencer'', July 16, 2003. Retrieved March 10, 2008.</ref>\n\nAccording to a disclosure form filed with the clerk of the House of Representatives, the nonprofit organization ''Life for Relief and Development'' paid McDermott's $5,510 travel expenses for the Iraq trip. On March 26, 2008, a Bush Administration indictment accused Muthanna Al-Hanooti of arranging for the trip and paying for it with funds from [[Saddam Hussein]]'s intelligence agency, the IIS.<ref>{{cite news |title=Indictment: Hussein fed money to spy for U.S. officials' trip|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/03/26/iraq.trip/index.html |accessdate= 2008-03-26 | work=CNN |date=March 26, 2008}}</ref> Ultimately these charges were dropped; Al-Hanooti was convicted of attempting to sell Iraqi oil to raise money for humanitarian purposes without permission of the U.S. Treasury.<ref>{{cite web |title=From spy to a patriot: Muthanna al-Hanooti\n |url=http://www.arabamericannews.com/news/index.php?mod=article&cat=OtherOpinions&article=4026 |publisher=arabamericannews.com|accessdate =2011-06-02 }}</ref>\n\n;African Growth and Opportunity Act of 2004\nThis act lowered tariffs and spurred apparel trade with many African countries. The AGOA has brought approximately 15,000 jobs and $340 million in foreign investment to some of the poorest nations in sub-Saharan Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agoa.info/index.php?view=download&story=legal |title= Resource on the African Growth and Opportunities Act |publisher=AGOA.info |date= |accessdate=April 11, 2013}}</ref> On August 22, 2007, McDermott was [[knight]]ed by [[Letsie III of Lesotho|King Letsie III]] of [[Lesotho]], in recognition of McDermott's leadership on the Act.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/local/330860_mcdermott08.html |title=McDermott knighted by king of Lesotho |publisher=Seattlepi.com |date=September 7, 2007 |accessdate=August 29, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.house.gov/mcdermott/pr070907.shtml Congressman Jim McDermott \u2013 News \u2013 Rep. McDermott Knighted by King in Lesotho, South Africa<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n;Violence Against Women and Justice Department Reauthorization Act of 2005\nThis piece of legislation strengthened privacy and confidentiality of people already receiving care under the Act and modernized it by prohibiting cyberstalking as defined under the law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delawarefederallawyers.com/news.cfm/Article/63826/McDermott-succeeds-with-Federal-Law.html |title=delawarefederallawyers.com |publisher=delawarefederallawyers.com |date= |accessdate=April 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\n;Pledge of Allegiance\nOn April 28, 2004, Congressman McDermott omitted the phrase \"under God\" while leading the House in reciting the [[Pledge of Allegiance]].  The incident occurred after [[atheist]] [[Michael Newdow]] lost his court case to have the phrase \"under God\" dropped from the Pledge, and after McDermott had voted against a congressional resolution that called for overturning a court ruling that declared the phrase unconstitutional.  In 1954, during the [[McCarthy era]] and communism scare, Congress had passed a bill, which was signed into law, to add the words \"under God.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.religioustolerance.org/nat_pled1.htm |title=Pledge of Allegiance and its \"under God\" phrase |publisher=Religioustolerance.org |date= |accessdate=April 11, 2013}}</ref> McDermott later stated that he had  \"reverted to the pledge as it was written and taught in the public schools throughout my childhood\", as the phrase \"under God\" was added in 1954, the year in which McDermott graduated from high school;<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.seattlepi.com/national/171126_jim29.html | work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer | first1=Wyatt | last1=Buchanan | title=McDermott's pledge error blamed on a childhood moment | date=April 28, 2004}}</ref> he turned 18 in late December of that year, after graduating.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=M000404 |title=McDERMOTT, James A. - Biographical Information |publisher=Bioguide.congress.gov |date= |accessdate=April 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\n;Boehner v. McDermott\nIn December 2004, the [[United States House Committee on Standards of Official Conduct|House Ethics Committee]] investigated McDermott over the leaking of an illegally recorded telephone conversation during a 1997 committee investigation of then-Speaker [[Newt Gingrich]].\n\nIn the conversation, Mr. Gingrich, his lawyer and several other Republican Congressmen discussed how Gingrich's Congressional allies should deal with the political consequences of his admission that he had violated House ethics rules by giving inaccurate information to the House Ethics Committee for its inquiry into his use of tax-exempt funds. Democrats have described the conversation as evidence that Mr. Gingrich broke an agreement with the Ethics Committee that he would not orchestrate a politically motivated response to those committee findings.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9800E0D91F38F935A25752C0A961958260&scp=2&sq=McDermott%20tunrs%20over%20intercepted%20conference%20call&st=cse |work=New York Times | accessdate=January 16, 2010 |title= Inquiry on Gingrich Call to Look at Plausibility of Florida Couple's Account |first=Neil A. |last=Lewis |date=January 16, 1997}}</ref>\n\nThe recording was made by John and Alice Martin, who claimed that they had overheard the conversation on a police scanner, decided to record it for posterity's sake, and then decided that it might be important for the Ethics Committee to hear.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1997/01/13/tape/index.shtml | work=CNN | accessdate=May 6, 2010 | title=Potentially Illegal Gingrich Tape Turned Over To Criminal Investigators}}</ref> The Martins gave the tape to McDermott because he was the senior Democrat on the Ethics Committee.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gray|first=Jerry|title=Florida Couple Are Charged In Taping of Gingrich Call|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/04/24/us/florida-couple-are-charged-in-taping-of-gingrich-call.html?ref=alicehmartin|accessdate=June 28, 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=April 24, 1997}}</ref> Within two days, reportedly after the Republican Ethics Committee Chair Nancy L. Johnson refused to allow a vote on making the tape part of the committee's records, sending the tape to the Justice Department, or taking any action against participants in the conversation,<ref>{{cite news|last=Gray|first=Jerry|title=Democrat Quits Ethics Panel Over Leak of Gingrich Tape|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/01/15/us/democrat-quits-ethics-panel-over-leak-of-gingrich-tape.html|accessdate=July 11, 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=January 15, 1997}}</ref> and over the warning of the Committee's counsel of possible legal liability, McDermott gave the tape to several media outlets, including the ''[[New York Times]].''\n\nRep. [[John Boehner]], who was part of the Gingrich conversation, sued McDermott in his capacity as a private citizen, seeking punitive damages for violations of his First Amendment rights.<ref>{{cite news|last=Alvarez|first=Lisette|title=Congressman Sues a Colleague Over Disclosing G.O.P. Talks|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/03/10/us/congressman-sues-a-colleague-over-disclosing-gop-talks.html|accessdate=July 11, 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=January 15, 1997}}</ref> After U.S. District Judge [[Thomas F. Hogan|Thomas Hogan]] ordered McDermott to pay Boehner for \"willful and knowing misconduct\" that \"rises to the level of malice\", McDermott appealed, arguing that since he had not created the recording, his actions were allowed under the First Amendment, and that ruling against him would have 'a huge chilling effect' on reporters and newsmakers alike. Eighteen news organizations \u2013 including ABC, NBC, CBS, CNN, The Associated Press, the ''New York Times'' and the ''[[Washington Post]]'' \u2014 filed a brief backing McDermott.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/politics/2002895236_webmcdermott28.html | work=The Seattle Times | title=Appeals Court rules against McDermott in taped call dispute | first=Matthew | last=Daly | date=March 28, 2006}}</ref> On March 29, 2006, the court ruled 2\u20131 that McDermott violated federal law when he turned over the illegally recorded tape to the media outlets, ordering McDermott to pay Boehner's legal costs (over $600,000) plus $60,000 in damages. On June 26, 2006, the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit]] vacated the judgment, deciding to re-hear the case with all nine judges.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/06/26/AR2006062601135.html | work=The Washington Post | first=Matthew | last=Daly | accessdate=May 6, 2010 | title=Court to Hear Arguments in Taped Call Case | date=June 26, 2006}}</ref> However, a split 4 to 1 to 4 en banc decision in ''Boehner v. McDermott'', 484 F.3d 573 (D.C. Cir. 2007) affirmed the three-judge panel, but on different grounds;<ref>{{cite web|author=Posted by ossma003 on October 21, 2009 2:49 PM |url=http://blog.lib.umn.edu/cla/discoveries/2009/10/full_dc_circuit_rules_mcdermot.html |title=CLA Publications: Full D.C. Circuit Rules McDermott Had No First Amendment Right to Leak Phone Tape Due to Ethics Committee Rules |publisher=Blog.lib.umn.edu |date=October 21, 2009 |accessdate=April 11, 2013}}</ref> the Supreme Court declined review.<ref>[http://www.politico.com/blogs/thecrypt/0707/McDermott_seeks_Supreme_Court_review_of_Boehner_lawsuit.html#comments The Crypt's Blog \u2013 Politico.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/POLITICS/12/03/scotus.call/index.html | work=CNN | title=Justices steer clear of lawmakers' feud | date=December 3, 2007 | accessdate=May 6, 2010}}</ref> On March 31, 2008, Chief Judge [[Thomas F. Hogan|Thomas Hogan]] of the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia]] ordered McDermott to pay Boehner $1.05 million in attorney's fees, costs and interest.  McDermott also paid over $60,000 in fines and close to $600,000 in his own legal fees.<ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/02/washington/02mcdermott.html?ref=us \"Lawmaker Must Pay $1 Million in Legal Fees\"], Associated Press (''International Herald Tribune''), April 2, 2008.</ref>\n\nThe Ethics Committee formally rebuked McDermott in 2006, writing he had \"violated ethics rules by giving reporters access to an illegally taped telephone call involving Republican leaders a decade ago.  Rep. McDermott's secretive disclosures to the news media ... risked undermining the ethics process\" and that McDermott's actions \"were not consistent with the spirit of the committee.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2003473288_mcdermott12m.html | work=The Seattle times | first=Alicia| last=Mundy | accessdate=July 11, 2011 | title=Ethics panel rebukes McDermott | date=December 12, 2006}}</ref> Previously, the Martins pleaded guilty to violating the [[Electronic Communications Privacy Act]]. In 1997, Gingrich was reprimanded by the House for providing false information to the Ethics Committee and he agreed to reimburse $300,000 in costs.\n\n;Depleted Uranium Study Act of 2006\nThis amendment to the Defense Authorization Act of 2006 directed the Department of Defense to study possible adverse health effects of the use of depleted uranium by the US military on servicemembers, employees and their families.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washblog.com/story/2006/10/3/151021/179 |title=McDermott-Cantwell Depleted Uranium Study Amendment Passes Congress |publisher=Washblog |date=October 3, 2006 |accessdate=April 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\n;Fostering Connections to Success and Increasing Adoptions Act of 2008\nA reform in the American foster care system, this legislation addresses needs affecting foster children in the United States; it extends federal foster care payments until children are 21 years old, provides federal support for relatives caring for foster children, increases access to foster care and adoption services by to Native American tribes, and improves oversight of the health and education needs of children in foster care.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcdermott.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=44&Itemid=41 |title=Rep. McDermott\u2019s Foster Care Legislation Signed Into Law |publisher=Mcdermott.house.gov |date=October 8, 2008 |accessdate=April 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\n;Unemployment Compensation Extension Acts of 2008\u20132009\nMcDermott has overseen{{citation needed|date=June 2013}} the emergency unemployment compensation extensions during the recession that began in 2008 under the George W. Bush Administration and has continued into the administration of Barack Obama.<ref>{{cite web|author=Posted on September 23, 2009 by Jay Sumner |url=http://www.dcemploymentlawupdate.com/tags/unemployment-compensation-exte/ |title=: Unemployment Compensation Extension Act : Washington D.C. Employment Law Update |publisher=Dcemploymentlawupdate.com |date=September 23, 2009 |accessdate=April 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\n;Ft. Lawton Legislation\nH.R. 3174 required the US Army Board for Correction of Military Records to review dozens of convictions that followed the [[Fort Lawton Riot]]. The Board uncovered \"egregious error\" in the prosecution, overturned the convictions, issued retroactive honorable discharges to the defendants and ordered back pay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historylink.org/index.cfm?DisplayPage=output.cfm&File_Id=7378|title=Riot involving African American soldiers occurs at Fort Lawton and an Italian POW is lynched on August 14, 1944.|author=Heather MacIntosh, Priscilla Long, David Wilma|publisher=HistoryLink.org|date=July 6, 2005|accessdate=July 31, 2011}}</ref> H.R. 5130 provided that such payments, which were otherwise of amounts considered nominal, to include interest.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2008267860_lawton15m.html|title=Ft. Lawton soldiers get back pay|publisher=Seattle Times|date=October 15, 2008|accessdate=July 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\n;Worker, Home ownership, and Business Assistance Act of 2009\nThe purpose of this act was to encourage job creation, strengthen the economic recovery, and assist those unable to find jobs during the serious economic downturn that began in 2008.<ref>{{USBill |111|HR|3548|pipe=Bill Summary & Status; 111th Congress (2009 - 2010); H.R.3548 |site=yes}}</ref> While the bill had unrelated provisions, the primary focus was on the extension of the $8,000 first-time home buyer tax credit; opinion is divided as to the effectiveness of the program.<ref>{{cite news|last=KOCIENIEWSKI|first=David|title=Mixed Results for Home Buyer Tax Credit|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/27/business/27home.html|work=Home Buyer Tax Credit|accessdate=June 23, 2011|date=April 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\n;Conflict Minerals Trade Act of 2010\nThis legislation requires publicly traded companies in the United States exercise due diligence to ensure that [[conflict minerals]] (gold, tin, tantalum and tungsten) in their products do not come from mines funding civil war in the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]] (DRC). Originally proposed as a standalone bill, it became section 1502 of the 2010 [[Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act#Disclosures on Conflict Materials in or Near the Democratic Republic of the Congo|Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act]]. A [[United Nations Security Council]] committee reported that this legislation was a \"catalyst\" for efforts to save lives by cutting off a key source of funding for armed groups <ref name=interim>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.un.org/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=S/2011/345\n|title=Interim report of the Group of Experts on the DRC\n|author=Security Council Committee established pursuant to resolution 1533 (2004) concerning the Democratic Republic of the Congo\n|date=June 11, 2011\n|accessdate=July 11, 2011\n|publisher=United Nations}}</ref> at a cost to American firms of approximately $8 billion per year.<ref>{{cite web|last=National Association of Manufacturers|title=Letter to Mary L. Shapiro|url=http://www.nam.org/~/media/E68D6C3155B34BE5A32206B0BB74BC6E/Final_NAM_Conflict_Minerals_Comments.pdf|accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref>  \n\n;Tax Parity for Health Plan Beneficiaries Act 2010, 2011\nMcDermott sponsored a bill which would have eliminated the tax burden incurred by married same sex couples, same-sex and opposite-sex domestic partners. The bill also would have ensured that domestic partners of federal civilian employees receive the same health care benefits as married spouses, including retirement, compensation for work injuries, and full life and health insurance benefits. It was eventually folded into and taken out of the House Health Care Bill in 2010, and has been referred to committee both times, where it died. Versions of this bill were co-sponsored under McDermott's leadership since the 106th Congress with Republican Senator Gordon Smith of Oregon. The 2010 (111th Congress) and 2011 (112th Congress) bills were co-sponsored by Democratic Senator Chuck Schumer of New York.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2011/06/09/mcdermott-introduces-pro-gay-tax-equity-bill/ |title=McDermott introduces pro-gay tax equity bill|last=Johnson |first=Chris |work=[[Washington Blade]] |date=June 9, 2011 |accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\n;Federal Reserve Transparency Act\nIn April 2012, McDermott was one of over 270 congressmen and congresswomen who co-sponsored the [[Federal Reserve Transparency Act]], which will \"require a full audit of the Board of Governors of the [[Federal Reserve System]] and the Federal Reserve banks by the [[Comptroller General of the United States]] before the end of 2012\" if it is passed.<ref>[http://www.dailypaul.com/155726/update-hr-459-55-co-sponsors Update - Audit The Fed: HR 459 - 271 Co-sponsors]</ref>\n\n;The Internet Gambling Regulation and Tax Enforcement Act\nIn June 2011, McDermott introduced The Internet Gambling Regulation and Tax Enforcement Act (H.R. 2230) along with [[John B. T. Campbell III|John Campbell]] (R-Calif.) and [[Barney Frank]] (D-Mass).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/167091-house-internet-gambling-bill-would-require-withholding-taxes-on-winnings |title=House Internet gambling bill would require withholding taxes on winnings|last=Kasperowicz |first=Pete |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=June 17, 2011 |accessdate=January 3, 2011}}</ref> This represented McDermott\u2019s fifth introduction of such an act, which would offer a tax structure should [[online gambling]] become fully legalized and regulated within the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livecasinodirect.com/guide/gambling-laws/usa/online-gambling-law/ |title=McDermott bill to decriminalize online gaming |publisher=Livecasinodirect.com |date=April 6, 2010 |accessdate=April 11, 2013}}</ref>\n;Ways and Means Committee Hearing on 2011-2013 IRS Scandal\nOn June 6, 2013 McDermott addressed victims of the IRS Scandal, showing sympathy and publicly stating that what had occurred was unacceptable, while also pointing out that the conservative groups would not have been targeted at all had they not filed for tax relief. Congressman Paul Ryan subsequently suggested that blaming the victims was inappropriate, and Fox News anchor Megyn Kelly interviewed Congressman McDermott on less than cordial terms, causing McDermott to demand she stop putting words in his mouth.\n\n===Committee assignments===\n[[File:WashingtonSeventhCongressDistrict.jpg|thumb|fight|200px|{{ushr|Washington|7|}}]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Committee on Ways and Means]]'''\n**[[United States House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Health|Subcommittee on Health]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on the Budget|Committee on the Budget]]'''\n\nFormerly ranking majority leader, then, in 1995, as the minority member of the [[Ethics Committee]] after Republicans retook control of the House.\n\n===Caucus memberships===\nMcDermott belongs to several dozen Congressional caucuses, and co-chairs the following caucuses:\n*[[Congressional HIV/AIDS Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Progressive Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Kidney Caucus]]\n\n==Personal life==\nHe has two adult children and three grandchildren.<ref>[http://www.house.gov/mcdermott/biography.shtml Retrieved 2007-03-25.]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Physicians in US Congress]]\n==References==\n<!-- Please do not add a scrollbox around this reference list. They are not allowed per the following discussion http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Templates_for_deletion/Log/2007_June_11#Template:Scrollref -->\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://mcdermott.house.gov/ Congressman Jim McDermott] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.mcdermottforcongress.com/ Jim McDermott for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Washington/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Jim_McDermott_%5BD-7%5D}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = M000404 | ballot = Jim_McDermott | nndb = 700/000039583 | votesmart = 27128 | govtrack = 400262 | opencong = 400262 | rollcall = 518 | politifact = jim-mcdermott | fec = H8WA07132 | opensecrets = N00009829 | assets = james-mcdermott | legistorm = 361/Rep_James_Adelbert_McDermott.html | followthemoney = | ontheissues = House/Jim_McDermott.htm | congress = jim-mcdermott/766 | worldcat = | cspan = 5761 | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = gIQApQvNKP}}\n*[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/rep